    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">
Chrusch&apos;s view on the seven great myths is quite interesting.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="37" relname="span">  I can recall 
several of these myths.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="35" relname="preparation">

Myth #2:</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="19" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> Online forms during the mid ninetys consisted on 3 -5 
pages</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="16" relname="span"> and many times users would abondon registering, ordering, or 
answering information from online surveys.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="35" relname="span">  Online commerce now have 1 
form to submit an order (e.g. 
Amazon.com), registering, and online surveys.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="condition"> 
If a form is more than 1 page,</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="30" relname="span"> users are now informed of their progress or 
the number of pages left to complete.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="26" relname="preparation">


Myth #4: </segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="8" relname="antithesis">
I have found usablity to be neither intelligence nor common sense as much.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="26" relname="span">  
Many times it is based on culture.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="24" relname="contrast">  Americans have a tendency to read from 
left to right.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="24" relname="contrast">  Whereas other countries read from right to left or top to 
bottom.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="25" relname="span">  Yet many applications/websites use this left to right approach.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="31" relname="preparation">

Myth #7: </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="23" relname="condition"> 
If 99% of users read either the documentation or reference materials, </segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="31" relname="span">
many tutorial companies would be out of business.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="29" relname="span"> Many of the books that 
novice user but are &quot;Quick Guide to...&quot; or &quot;Dummies&quot; books on computers.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="28" relname="span"> 
In addition, the online tutorials provide streamline media that American 
have become accustomed to, &quot;television.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="27" relname="span">  As an educator, many of my 
students are encourage to use streamline media instead of reading 
manuals, docs., and plan-old verbal instructions.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="15" relname="elaboration">  Perhaps, learing needs to 
degress to old-common books, </segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="38" relname="evaluation">

As technology continues, I strongly believe 7 common myths will become 
&quot;20&quot; common myths.</segment>
